@node "Changes" "Changes Since Last Release"
@{fg shine}@{bg fill} NetPar Client @{fg text}@{bg back}- Added a 68000, 68020, 68040, and 68060 version
                of client. I doubt that you will notice a speed
                difference using these programs since most of
                the code is device/network specific. I made many
                internal changes getting ready for lpr/lpd
                complience. You can identify the different versions
                by using the AmigaDOS "version" command from
                cli/shell.

@{fg shine}@{bg fill}NetPar Server @{fg text}@{bg back}- Added @{b}LOG@{ub} keyword and @{b}LOGFILE=@{ub} parameter. Adding
                @{b}LOG@{ub} to the list a server Args will create a file
                called @{b}@{fg shine}T:NetParServer.log@{ub}@{fg text} . The@{b} LOGFILE=@{ub} option
                will let you place the logfile anywhere you want
                it to be. The logfile contains the IP address of
                the requesting client, the date of the request, the
                time of the request, how many bytes transferred for
                good connections and/or an error message for bad
                connections.

@{fg shine}@{bg fill}TestPar       @{fg text}@{bg back}- No changes






*
@endnode

@node "InstallClient" "NetPar Client Installation Notes"

             @{b}Client Side Installation Notes:@{ub}


@{fg shine}Client Side: The Machine without a printer@{fg text}

What the install script does:

@{u}Step #1)@{uu}
         Renames your current parallel.device to 
         orig_parallel.device.

        @{b}@{i} Note:@{ub}@{ui} @{fg shine}The installer script will skip this step
               if orig_parallel.device already exists.)@{fg text}

@{u}Step #2)@{uu}
         Copies the NetPar.device into the devs: directory. Renames
         NetPar.device to parallel.device. There are two versions
         of the NetPar.device. One is used to give you debug
         information should you run into problems. Only use
         this version if you are having problems as it will run
         slow. It will write two debug logs in your SYS: directory.
         The other version of NetPar.device is for every day use.
         The NetPar Client Installer script will ask you which
         client you want to use (Normal or Debug).
         
        @{b}@{i} Note:@{ub}@{ui}@{fg shine} The installer script also comes with a "Remove"
         option. This option is only available to the "Intermediate"
         or "Expert" mode. Remove will reset your system back to 
         it's original settings (no NetPar Client installed). If
         you wish to change from Normal to Debug (or vice versa)
         you must first use the "Remove" option to remove 
         NetPar Client from your machine. Then you can install the
         Client you need.@{fg text}


@{u}Step #3)@{uu}
         You must identify who your server side printer host is.
         It can be identified by either the IP address or by the
         machine name. The installation script then sets a
         PrintHOST environment variable to the machine you just
         identified. This PrintHOST variable can be changed on the
         fly (manually) to re-direct the NetPar output to another
         server.

@{u}Step #4)@{uu} All done. Setup Server and Print!
@endnode

@node "InstallServer" "NetPar Server Installation Steps"

                  @{b}Server Side Installation Steps:@{ub}

@{fg shine}Server Side - Machine with the printer@{fg text}

@{u}Step #1)@{uu}
        Copy the NetParServer into a common directory.

          @{fg shine}AmiTCP@{fg text} - Place it into AmiTCP:serv directory.

         @{b}@{fg shine} @{ub}Maimi@{fg text} - Create a Maimi:serv directory and place it there

          @{b}@{i}Note:@{ub}@{ui} @{fg shine}You can place the Server anywhere as long as you
          let the InetD Daemon know where it is. (See step #2)@{fg text}

@{u}Step #2)@{uu}
        Set up the Inet Daemon to run the NetPar Server

          @{b}@{fg shine}AmiTCP@{ub}@{fg text} -
              Edit the Amitcp:db/inetd.conf file to run the
              NetParServer. The entry should look like this:

@{i}@{fg shine}printer stream tcp nowait root amitcp:serv/NetParServer NetPrint@{ui}@{fg text}

              The above setting will send any incoming printouts
              to the PAR: device (The native Amiga port). If you
              own a GVP I/O extender you can redirect the server
              output by passing a DEVICE= option like this:

@{i}@{fg shine}printer stream tcp nowait root amitcp:serv/NetParServer NetPrint DEVICE=GVPPAR0:@{ui}@{fg text}

              MultiFace II and III users can send the output to
              PIT0: device. Any AmigaDos device will work. Serial
              port printers can be sent to SER: for example.

             @{b}@{i} Note:@{ub}@{ui} @{fg shine}There is no spaces in the DEVICE= parameter. The
              above entry is all on one line.@{fg text}

            @{b}@{bg shine}  WARNING:@{ub}@{fg fill} You can also send your output to a file    @{fg text}@{bg back}
            @{fg fill}@{bg shine}  using the DEVICE= option. BE CAREFUL. Setting it to @{fg text}@{bg back}
            @{fg fill}@{bg shine}  DEVICE=s:startup-sequence will overwrite your       @{fg text}@{bg back} 
            @{fg fill}@{bg shine}  startup-sequence.@{fg text}@{bg back}


              If you run into @{" problems " link "Problems" 0} you can add the DEBUG option as
              well. Like this:

@{i}@{fg shine}printer stream tcp nowait root amitcp:serv/NetParServer NetPrint DEBUG@{ui}@{fg text}

              This will send debug information to the Amitcp system log.
        
          @{b}@{fg shine}Miami@{ub}@{fg text} -
              Go into the Database and select InetD for input. Add the
              following entries into the Miami User interface:

                  @{fg shine}Service  = printer
                  Socket   = stream
                  Protocol = tcp
                  Wait     = nowait
                  User     = root@{fg text}
                    (The above entries must be in lower case. Otherwise
                     the server will refuse to connect)
                  @{fg shine}Server   = Miami:serv/NetParServer
                  Name     = NetPrint
                  Args     = See below@{fg text}

             Just as in AmiTCP, the NetPar Server accepts only two
             Args. The first is the DEVICE= option. NetPar defaults
             to PAR: so nothing is needed if you want to send your
             output to the PAR: device. If you have a GVP I/O Extender
             or MultiFace II/III, you could send the output to those
             cards (using DEVICE=GVPPAR0: or DEVICE=PIT0: )
             with this Arg. The DEBUG arg will send debug information
             to the Miami system log. This log is useful when it
             comes to troubleshooting @{" problems " link "Problems" 0} in NetPar. Finally,
             as in AmiTCP, the same Warning applies:

             @{b}@{bg shine}  WARNING:@{ub}@{fg fill} You can also send your output to a file    @{fg text}@{bg back}
             @{fg fill}@{bg shine}  using the DEVICE= option. BE CAREFUL. Setting it to @{fg text}@{bg back}
             @{fg fill}@{bg shine}  DEVICE=s:startup-sequence will overwrite your       @{fg text}@{bg back}
             @{fg fill}@{bg shine}  startup-sequence.@{fg text}@{bg back}



@{u}Step #3)@{uu} Restart your protocol stack and you are ready.



*
@endnode

@node "Security" "Security Features"


 @{b}Or the current lack of Security@{ub}

   Currently there are no security features built into
   the NetPar Server. I have plans to add some but for
   now, the only protection you get is from your
   protocol stack:

       @{fg shine}AmiTCP@{fg text} - You can allow/deny access to NetPar by
       editing the AmiTCP:db/inet.access file. See the
       AmiTCP docs for details.

       @{fg shine}Miami@{fg text}  - I know of no way to restrict access to NetPar
       from Miami. It might be there, I just don't know where.
       If you know how to do this, please e-mail me so I can
       include it in the next release.


   This is only a temporary problem. I plan on adding security
   features into NetPar in the near @{" future " link "Future" 0}.
@endnode

@node "Problems" "NetPar Troubleshooting Guide"

        @{b} NetPar Troubleshooting Guide@{ub}

     Below is a quick list of easy fixes to NetPar. If none of these
     help you, I have included a step-by-step guide to get NetPar running
     on your machine.

   @{" Step-By-Step " link "StepByStepAmiTCP" 0} for AmiTCP
   @{" Step-By-Step " link "StepByStepMiami" 0} for Miami

   @{" Problem #1 " link "Problem1" 0}   Client Prints as normal, but no output is received
   @{" Problem #2 " link "Problem2" 0}   Client hangs up, refuses to print, must be reset.
   @{" Problem #3 " link "Problem3" 0}   Client Guru's as soon as printer is accessed.
   @{" Problem #4 " link "Bugs" 0}   Server no longer accepts input from Client
   @{" Problem #5 " link "Bugs" 0}   Can't print from two Clients at the same time



   @{fg fill}@{bg shine} Troubleshooting hint:@{fg text}@{bg back} Uninstall the NetPar Client and reinstall
    the debug version when having problems. Add the DEBUG flag on
    the Server. This will aid you and me in troubleshooting any
    problems you may have.

    The NetPar client will write to debug logs to our SYS: drive.
    They are called NetParClient.log and NetParInit.log . Please
    include these files when asking for help......
@endnode

@node "StepByStepAmiTCP" "Troubleshooting NetPar - AmiTCP Step by Step"

@{b}@{i}  If you made it here, I guess I can assume that you are      
  having problems getting NetPar to work with AmiTCP. I have
  included this step-by-step installation method to help      
  you (and me) find your problem. Although I have made every  
  effort to make NetPar installations as simple as possible,  
  sometimes SH*T happens. When it does, I don't want you      
  to feel like you have been hit by Micro$oft and have no     
  tools to find and fix your problem. Networks can be tricky, 
  and this is my commitment to helping you.                   @{ub}@{ui}

 Should you run into any errors while doing these steps,
 the errors need to be fixed before proceeding to the next
 step. The logic used in this guide will find your problem
 and hopefully get you up and running quickly. If not, you
 have my e-mail for easy flaming.@{b}@{i}

 @{ui}First we Play with the Server.@{ub}

 @{b}@{u}Step #1)@{ub}@{uu} On the Server (the side with the printer),

          Go into the AmiTCP:db/inetd.conf and make the following
          entry. (Comment out your old entry if needed.)

@{fg shine}printer stream tcp nowait root AmiTCP:serv/NetParServer NetPrint DEVICE=SYS:TestPrint DEBUG@{fg text}

          These settings will take the printer out of the failure
          loop. We can test your server configuration without
          needing to have a printer. Later on we will add the
          printer and test it.

 @{b}@{u}Step #2)@{ub}@{uu} Bring AmiTCP online (on the Server). You
          will need to stop-and start AmiTCP in order for the changes
          to be seen.

 @{b}@{u}Step #3)@{ub}@{uu} Copy the TestPar program on to the server ( I would
          put it on my Ram Disk: ) Now double-click on the
          TestPar icon in order to run the test page. Your
          message should look like this:

  @{fg fill}@{bg shine}===Begin Message===@{fg text}@{bg back}
  @{fg shine}*

  Welcome to NetPar Test Client

  Attempting to open bsdsocket.library >>-> Complete

  Testing NetPar Server

       PrintHOST = ->localhost<-

  Opening Socket       >>-> Complete
  Connecting to Server >>-> Complete
  Sending Test Page    >>-> Complete



  exit TestPar - Test Complete@{fg text}
  @{fg fill}@{bg shine}===End Message===@{fg text}@{bg back}

          @{bg shine}Note: Be patient when program is running the@{bg back}
          @{bg shine}"Connecting to Server" message. It may take a few minutes@{bg back}
          @{bg shine}to report what your connection error is.@{bg back}

          Check to see if the program recognized that we were
          testing the NetPar Server. It is an error if TestPar
          didn't recognize the server (as localhost). Also
          check the AmiTCP System Log. It should show a
          connection, with 3314 bytes transferred, followed
          by a closed connection.

          @{fg shine}@{bg fill}@{" Errors " link "StepErrors" 0}@{fg text}@{bg back} explained here.


 @{b}@{u}Step #4)@{ub}@{uu} Bring AmiTCP offline on the server. If this means that
          you have to re-boot your machine, then go ahead and do it.


@{b} Now we will be checking out your network connection between the
 machines.@{ub}

 @{b}@{u}Step #5)@{ub}@{uu} Bring AmiTCP online on the server.

 @{b}@{u}Step #6)@{ub}@{uu} Install NetPar debug client on your cllient machine.

   @{bg shine}Note: You may need to remove the original NetPar client@{bg back}
   @{bg shine}first. Just use the Remove option in the installer script.@{bg back}

          Bring AmiTCP online on your client machine.

 @{b}@{u}Step #7)@{ub}@{uu} Checkout the network connection by pinging the
           server from the client like this from shell/cli:

   @{fg shine}ping $PrintHOST@{fg text}

          Pinging $PrintHOST will make sure that the NetPar client
          has the right settings.

          If this doesn't work, you have a network problem
          (with routing) or a PrintHOST naming problem. If
          you are unsure of the error message you were given,
          you can send it to me and I'll do my best to help you.

 @{b}@{u}Step #8)@{ub}@{uu} Copy the TestPar program on to the client ( I would
          put it on my Ram Disk: ) Now double-click on the
          TestPar icon in order to run the test page. Your
          message should look like this (mikey is my PrinHOST):

  @{fg fill}@{bg shine}===Begin Message===@{fg text}@{bg back}
  @{fg shine}*

  Welcome to NetPar Test Client

  Attempting to open bsdsocket.library >>-> Complete

  Testing NetPar Client

       PrintHOST = ->mikey<-

  Opening Socket       >>-> Complete
  Connecting to Server >>-> Complete
  Sending Test Page    >>-> Complete



  exit TestPar - Test Complete@{fg text}
  @{fg fill}@{bg shine}===End Message===@{fg text}@{bg back}

         @{bg shine}Note: Be patient when program is running the@{bg back}
         @{bg shine}"Connecting to Server" message. It may take a few minutes@{bg back}
         @{bg shine}to report what your connection error is.@{bg back}

         Check to see if the program recognized that we were
         testing the NetPar Client. It is an error if TestPar
         didn't recognize the client. Make sure that the
         PrintHOST = is the name of your server.  Also
         check the AmiTCP System Log. It should show a
         connection, with 3314 bytes transferred, followed
         by a closed connection.

         @{fg shine}@{bg fill}@{" Errors " link "StepErrors" 0}@{fg text}@{bg back} explained here.


 @{b}Network testing is complete. Now we test the NetPar Client.@{ub}

 @{b}@{u}Step #9)@{ub}@{uu} On your client, copy your S:Startup-sequence to PAR:
         (example 16.Ram Disk:>copy S:statup-sequence to par:) from
         shell/cli. The Server AmiTCP System Log should record the
         connection and transfer of the file. On the server you should
         get a SYS:TestPrint file that is the same as your client
         side s:startup-sequence.

         @{fg shine}@{bg fill}@{" Errors " link "StepErrors" 0}@{fg text}@{bg back} explained here.

 @{b}@{u}Step #10)@{ub}@{uu} If everything works to this point, add your printer
         to the server by changing the DEVICE= back to your AmigaDOS
         device (i.e. PAR:) on the server. When you are complete,
         checkout the printer by doing steps #2) through  #9) If you
         run into a problem here, it is probably the AmigaDOS device
         you selected or something to do with your printer or printer
         connection.

 @{b}@{u}Step #11)@{ub}@{uu} Remove debug from the server an again checkout the
         system by performing steps #2) and #9) of this step-by-step
         guide. A problem in this area belongs to me. Please e-mail
         to me the details as well as a copy of the debug logs.

 @{b}@{u}Step #12)@{ub}@{uu} Remove the NetPar debug Client and reinstall the
         regular NetPar Client. You can test it by performing steps #2)
         through #9) of this step-by-step guide. A problem in this
         area belongs to me. Please e-mail to me the details.

 @{b}@{u}Step #13)@{ub}@{uu} Be happy. You have overcome the problem. NetPar is
         installed on your network.



@{fg shine}Please let me know if my logic has helped you. I would love to hear any
success stories.@{fg text}


*
@endnode

@node "StepByStepMiami" "Troubleshooting NetPar - Miami Step by Step"

@{b}@{i}  If you made it here, I guess I can assume that you are      
  having problems getting NetPar to work with Miami. I have   
  included this step-by-step installation method to help      
  you (and me) find your problem. Although I have made every  
  effort to make NetPar installations as simple as possible,  
  sometimes SH*T happens. When it does, I don't want you      
  to feel like you have been hit by Micro$oft and have no     
  tools to find and fix your problem. Networks can be tricky, 
  and this is my commitment to helping you.                   @{ub}@{ui}

 Should you run into any errors while doing these steps,
 the errors need to be fixed before proceeding to the next
 step. The logic used in this guide will find your problem
 and hopefully get you up and running quickly. If not, you
 have my e-mail for easy flaming.@{b}@{i}

 @{ui}First we Play with the Server.@{ub}

 @{b}@{u}Step #1)@{ub}@{uu} On the Server (the side with the printer),

          Go into the Database and select InetD for input.
          Add the following entries into the Miami user
          interface:

             @{fg shine}Service  = printer
             Socket   = stream
             Protocol = tcp
             Wait     = nowait
             User     = root
               @{fg text}(Please note that all of the above entries need
                to be in lower case. Adding a upper case letter will
                cause the server to refuse connection.)
             @{fg shine}Server   = Miami:serv/NetParServer@{fg text}
               (If this is where the NetParServer is located)
            @{fg shine} Name     = NetPrint
             Args     = DEVICE=SYS:TestPrint DEBUG@{fg text}

          These settings will take the printer out of the failure
          loop. We can test your server configuration without
          needing to have a printer. Later on we will add the
          printer and test it.

 @{b}@{u}Step #2)@{ub}@{uu} Bring Miami online (on the Server).

 @{b}@{u}Step #3)@{ub}@{uu} Copy the TestPar program on to the server ( I would
          put it on my Ram Disk: ) Now double-click on the
          TestPar icon in order to run the test page. Your
          message should look like this:

  @{fg fill}@{bg shine}===Begin Message===@{fg text}@{bg back}
  @{fg shine}*

  Welcome to NetPar Test Client

  Attempting to open bsdsocket.library >>-> Complete

  Testing NetPar Server

       PrintHOST = ->localhost<-

  Opening Socket       >>-> Complete
  Connecting to Server >>-> Complete
  Sending Test Page    >>-> Complete



  exit TestPar - Test Complete@{fg text}
  @{fg fill}@{bg shine}===End Message===@{fg text}@{bg back}

          @{bg shine}Note: Be patient when program is running the@{bg back}
          @{bg shine}"Connecting to Server" message. It may take a few minutes@{bg back}
          @{bg shine}to report what your connection error is.@{bg back}

          Check to see if the program recognized that we were
          testing the NetPar Server. It is an error if TestPar
          didn't recognize the server (as localhost). Also
          check the Miami System Log. It should show a
          connection, with 3314 bytes transferred, followed
          by a closed connection.

          @{fg shine}@{bg fill}@{" Errors " link "StepErrors" 0}@{fg text}@{bg back} explained here.


 @{b}@{u}Step #4)@{ub}@{uu} Bring Miami offline on the server. If this means that
          you have to re-boot your machine, then go ahead and do it.


@{b} Now we will be checking out your network connection between the
 machines.@{ub}

 @{b}@{u}Step #5)@{ub}@{uu} Bring Miami on the server online.

 @{b}@{u}Step #6)@{ub}@{uu} Install NetPar debug client on your cllient machine.

   @{bg shine}Note: You may need to remove the original NetPar client@{bg back}
   @{bg shine}first. Just use the Remove option in the installer script.@{bg back}

          Bring Miami online on your client machine.

 @{b}@{u}Step #7)@{ub}@{uu} Checkout the network connection by pinging the
           server from the client like this from shell/cli:

   @{fg shine}MiamiPing $PrintHOST@{fg text}

          Pinging $PrintHOST will make sure that the NetPar client
          has the right settings.

          If this doesn't work, you have a network problem
          (with routing) or a PrintHOST naming problem. If
          you are unsure of the error message you were given,
          you can send it to me and I'll do my best to help you.

 @{b}@{u}Step #8)@{ub}@{uu} Copy the TestPar program on to the client ( I would
          put it on my Ram Disk: ) Now double-click on the
          TestPar icon in order to run the test page. Your
          message should look like this (mikey is my PrinHOST):

  @{fg fill}@{bg shine}===Begin Message===@{fg text}@{bg back}
  @{fg shine}*

  Welcome to NetPar Test Client

  Attempting to open bsdsocket.library >>-> Complete

  Testing NetPar Client

       PrintHOST = ->mikey<-

  Opening Socket       >>-> Complete
  Connecting to Server >>-> Complete
  Sending Test Page    >>-> Complete



  exit TestPar - Test Complete@{fg text}
  @{fg fill}@{bg shine}===End Message===@{fg text}@{bg back}

         @{bg shine}Note: Be patient when program is running the@{bg back}
         @{bg shine}"Connecting to Server" message. It may take a few minutes@{bg back}
         @{bg shine}to report what your connection error is.@{bg back}

         Check to see if the program recognized that we were
         testing the NetPar Client. It is an error if TestPar
         didn't recognize the client. Make sure that the
         PrintHOST = the name of your server.  Also
         check the Miami System Log. It should show a
         connection, with 3314 bytes transferred, followed
         by a closed connection.

         @{fg shine}@{bg fill}@{" Errors " link "StepErrors" 0}@{fg text}@{bg back} explained here.


 @{b}Network testing is complete. Now we test the NetPar Client.@{ub}

 @{b}@{u}Step #9)@{ub}@{uu} On your client, copy your S:Startup-sequence to PAR:
         (example 16.Ram Disk:>copy S:statup-sequence to par:) from
         shell/cli. The Server Miami System Log should record the
         connection and transfer of the file. On the server you should
         get a SYS:TestPrint file that is the same as your client
         side s:startup-sequence.

         @{fg shine}@{bg fill}@{" Errors " link "StepErrors" 0}@{fg text}@{bg back} explained here.

 @{b}@{u}Step #10)@{ub}@{uu} If everything works to this point, add your printer
         to the server by changing the DEVICE= back to your AmigaDOS
         device (i.e. PAR:) on the server. When you are complete,
         checkout the printer by doing steps #2) through  #9) If you
         run into a problem here, it is probably the AmigaDOS device
         you selected or something to do with your printer or printer
         connection.

 @{b}@{u}Step #11)@{ub}@{uu} Remove debug from the server an again checkout the
         system by performing steps #2) and #9) of this step-by-step
         guide. A problem in this area belongs to me. Please e-mail
         to me the details as well as a copy of the debug logs.

 @{b}@{u}Step #12)@{ub}@{uu} Remove the NetPar debug Client and reinstall the
         regular NetPar Client. You can test it by performing steps #2)
         through #9) of this step-by-step guide. A problem in this
         area belongs to me. Please e-mail to me the details.

 @{b}@{u}Step #13)@{ub}@{uu} Be happy. You have overcome the problem. NetPar is
         installed on your network.



@{fg shine}Please let me know if my logic has helped you. I would love to hear any
success stories.@{fg text}


*
@endnode

@node "StepErrors" "NetPar Step-By-Step Problem Help"

@{fg fill}@{bg shine} Step-by-Step Errors:@{fg text}@{bg back}


@{fg shine}@{bg fill} TestPar didn't recognize the Server@{fg text}@{bg back}

     You have a system variable called PrintHOST on your machine.
     TestPar thinks it is running as a client.

@{fg shine}@{bg fill} TestPar didn't recognize the Client@{fg text}@{bg back}

     You are missing the PrintHOST variable from your machine. It
     was either accidentally removed or the installation failed. This
     file must contain the name of your Server in order for the NetPar
     client to work.

@{fg shine}@{bg fill} Network Error@{fg text}@{bg back}

     Something in your network is configured incorrectly. The error
     message that proceeded the Network Error should point you to
     what needs to be changed in the network. If you are confused,
     please send the message to me (and as detailed as possible) a
     explanation of our setup. I will try to respond quickly. If I
     find a pattern of Network Errors, the fixes will be placed here.

@{fg shine}@{bg fill} Server Configuration Error@{fg text}@{bg back}

     Your server has refused to run the NetParServer program. Something
     is wrong with the installation (possibly my steps?). Again, if
     you cannot find the problem, let me know and I will try to help. If
     I see a common pattern I will include the fix here. As below:

         @{fg shine} Miami@{fg text} - Check PrintHOST case. The PrintHOST entry and the
                  Database-Hosts entry should have the exact
                  case (upper-lower).

         @{fg shine} Miami@{fg text} - Service = printer . "printer" must be in lower case or
                  server will refuse to connect.

@{fg shine}@{bg fill} Programmer Error@{fg text}@{bg back}

     I have assumed something about your system that is incorrect. I
     have left something out, or else my logic is flawed. Please send
     me the debug logs as well as the Error Message you encountered.


*
@endnode

@node "Problem1" "Where's my output?"
 @{b}Printed fine but no output.....@{ub}

   Two possible reasons.

      @{fg shine}#1)@{fg text} No Protocol stack is running.
           Check on AmiTCP or Miami. Protocol
           stack must be bsdsocket.library compatible

     @{fg shine} #2)@{fg text} Unable to connect to Printer Host. Make sure
          that you can get to the printer host by trying
          to "ping" that host.

 Finally, if these aren't the problem...Use the NetParClient.log
 for hints into why the connection can't get through.
@endnode

@node "Problem2" "Lost in Space"


@{b}Client takes forever and nothing happens...@{ub}

   @{fg shine}There is only one known reason why this happens:@{fg text}


   #1) Server client is unknown. See if
       you can "ping" the server.

   If this isn't the problem, run the debug version
   of NetPar Client and read the NetParClient.log
   in order to get some hints at what is going wrong.
@endnode

@node "Problem3" "Have you meet my Sister?"


@{b}Guru's as soon as printer is accessed.@{ub}

   @{fg shine}Not my fault man.@{fg text} I spent@{b}@{fg shine} WEEKS @{ub}@{fg text}trying to find this
   little bug.

   Turned out that my Sister had gone into preferences
   and selected a regular text file to be a printer
   driver. .... Selected correct printer driver and
   beat up little sister. Everything works fine now.
@endnode

@node "Bugs" "NetPar Known Problems"


     @{b} NetPar Known Bugs@{ub}


    @{fg highlight}  Actually there are two:@{fg text}

   ** Sometimes the NetPar Server will no longer accept input.
      My research has indicated that the Server has a old socket
      open and is still waiting for an EOF character to close
      the connection. This normally happens when the client side
      dies unexpectedly (I create these unexpected conditions all
      the time). I will be fixing this problem in the future by
      attaching a timeout on the socket connection and through
      spooling on the incoming printout.


      The only known method to recover from this condition is to
      reboot your machine. You might try to kill the protocol
      stack, or send a Ctrl-C to NetParServer, if you can. The
      problem hasn't happened enough for me to try these things
      and I will be surprise if it happens to you.......


   ** If two clients try to print to the same server, at the
      same time, only one will get through, the other will be
      rejected.

      This will also be fixed when spooling becomes available.

      @{fg shine}Please let me know if you encounter others. Some "bugs" are
      actually built-in safeguards for NetPar. See the
      @{" Problems? " link "Problems" 0} @{fg shine}section for details.@{fg text}


*
@endnode

